ings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Etton,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Elton (Berkshire, Cheshire, Derbyshire, Durham, Herefordshire, Huntingdonshire, Lancashire, and Nottinghamshire). The Eltons in Chesire, Derbyshire, and Durham are from Old English <i>ǣl</i> ‘eel’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’. Elton in Berkshire is from the Old English female personal name <i>Æthelflǣd</i> (composed of the elements <i>æthel</i> ‘noble’ + <i>flǣd</i> ‘beauty’). Both Elton in Herefordshire and in Nottinghamshire are from the Old English personal name <i>Ella</i> + <i>tūn</i>. The Berkshire origin for the surname is especially well represented.","Norwegian: habitational name from a farm name in eastern Norway, in Old Norse <i>Elgjartún</i> ‘enclosed sacred place’ (or fenced in for <i>elg</i> ‘moose’?)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":2,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":11,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Etton, Lord of Gilling was born in 1213, in Etton, Yorkshire, England, his father, Thomas de Etton, was 59 and his mother, Alice de Eggesholm, was 18. He had at least 1 son. He died about 1252, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1213–about 1252 (he was still alive in 1251/52)":"1213–umbes 1252","1213–1252":"1213–1252","1215–Male":"1215–Surnud","1217–Male":"1217–Surnud","1242–1315":"1242–1315","1154–1235":"1154–1235","1195–Female":"1195–Surnud","1154":"1154","1242":"1242","1252":"1252","1195":"1195","1217":"1217","1216":"1216","1315":"1315","1215":"1215","1213":"1213","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1212":"1212","about 1252 (he was still alive in 1251/52)":"umbes 1252","       1235":"1235","Etton,York,England":"Etton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Etton, Yorkshire, England":"Etton, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1213–about 1252 (he was still alive in 1251/52)":"1213–noin 1252","1213–1252":"1213–1252","1215–Male":"1215–Kuollut","1217–Male":"1217–Kuollut","1242–1315":"1242–1315","1154–1235":"1154–1235","1195–Female":"1195–Kuollut","1154":"1154","1242":"124